Q: JComboBox getSelectedItem() not finding the object (cannot be resolved) A: <p>I don't know who approved the publication, but the code you show doesn't compile...
Let's look at some problems:</p>
<ol>
<li>Class attributes:</li>
</ol>
<pre><code>public class BudgetBase extends JPanel {   
    JFrame topLevelFrame;  // top-level JFrame
    GridBagConstraints layoutConstraints = new GridBagConstraints(); 
    private JButton calculateButton;   
    private JButton exitButton; 
    private JTextField wagesField;  
    private JTextField loansField;   
    private JTextField otherIncomeField;   
    private JTextField totalIncomeField; 
    private JTextField foodField; 
    private JTextField rentField;  
    private JTextField otherSpendingField;  
    private JTextField totalSpendingField;  
    private JTextField deficitField; 
    String[] rate = {“/week”, “/month”, “/year”};
</code></pre>
<p><strong>wagesRateBox</strong> does not appear here, so in the <strong>calculateTotalSpending</strong> method, on the line <strong>String foodRate = foodRateBox.getSelectedItem();</strong>, I get a warning:</p>
<pre><code>cannot find symbol
 symbol: variable foodRateBox
 location: class BudgetBase
</code></pre>
<ol start="2">
<li>the <strong>JComboBox</strong> that does appear</li>
</ol>
<pre><code>private void initComponents() { 
      // I omit the other lines
    final JComboBox&lt;String&gt; wagesRateBox = new JComboBox&lt;String&gt;(rate);
}
</code></pre>
<p>Here it does appear as <strong>wagesRateBox</strong> (Should <strong>wagesRateBox</strong> be <strong>foodRateBox</strong>?), but not as an attribute, so it is only visible within this method.</p>
<p>A first step would be to declare <strong>foodRateBox</strong> as an attribute, but then another problem arises: the line <strong>String foodRate = foodRateBox.getSelectedItem();</strong> gives me the error:</p>
<pre><code>incompatible types: Object cannot be converted to String
</code></pre>
<p>because <strong>getSelectedItem()</strong> returns an <em>Object</em>, so the corresponding casting must be done.</p>

Q: Laravel - Hash input using SHA512 A: <pre><code>// Source - https://stackoverflow.com/a/56129334
// Posted by Dan
// Retrieved 2025-12-21, License - CC BY-SA 4.0

public function store(Request $request)
{
    $request-&gt;validate([
        'referenceID' =&gt; 'required',
        'phone_no' =&gt; 'required',
    ]);

    $referenceID = $request-&gt;referenceID;
    $phone_no = $request-&gt;phone_no;
    $hash = hash('sha512', $referenceID . $phone_no);

    $valrequest = Task::create(compact('referenceID', 'phone_no', 'hash'));

    return response()-&gt;json([
        'message' =&gt; 'Great success! New validation request created',
        'valrequest' =&gt; $valrequest, 201
    ]);
}
</code></pre>

Q: How to connect to SQL database with react? A: <p>How time flies ... Once this question was absurd ... today though ?</p>
<pre><code>import mysql from 'mysql2/promise';

const connection = await mysql.createConnection({
  host: process.env.DB_HOST,
  user: process.env.DB_USER,
  password: process.env.DB_PASS,
  database: process.env.DB_NAME,
});

type User = {
  id: number;
  username: string;
  email: string;
};

export default async function HomePage() {
  const [rows] = await connection.execute&lt;User[]&gt;('SELECT id, username, email FROM users LIMIT 20');

  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;h1&gt;Hello from React-that-finally-became-PHP!&lt;/h1&gt;
      &lt;h2&gt;List of Users&lt;/h2&gt;
      {rows.length === 0 ? (
        &lt;p&gt;No users found.&lt;/p&gt;
      ) : (
        &lt;ul&gt;
          {rows.map((user) =&gt; (
            &lt;li key={user.id}&gt;
              &lt;strong&gt;{user.username}&lt;/strong&gt; ({user.email})
            &lt;/li&gt;
          ))}
        &lt;/ul&gt;
      )}
    &lt;/div&gt;
  );
}
</code></pre>
<p>Full disclosure though. I would never advise anyone use this in something more than a weekend project. Or fun exercise to understand how Server components work, let alone allow this to go to production of any kind :D</p>

Q: Silent Bug on React JS Anime list A: <p>As already mentioned, you used wrong event on a button.
You can achieve what you want by replacing wrapping <code>div</code> with <code>form</code> and subscribing to <code>onSubmit</code> event. This event will carry value from wrapped <code>input</code> elements, which would simplify your code, because you don't need to perform DOM search for element and get form values directly on event object that is passed as parameter:</p>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false" data-console="true" data-babel="true" data-babel-preset-react="true" data-babel-preset-ts="false">
<div class="snippet-code">
<pre class="snippet-code-js lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>function AnimeList(){
    const [anime, setAnime] = React.useState(["Attack on Titan", "Kimi No Wa", "Sakamoto Days"])

    function handleAddAnime(e){
        e.preventDefault();
        setAnime([...anime, e.target.elements.animeInput.value]);
    }

    return(
        &lt;form onSubmit={handleAddAnime}&gt;
            &lt;h2&gt;Anime list&lt;/h2&gt;
            &lt;ul&gt;
                {anime.map((anime, index) =&gt; &lt;li key={index}&gt;{anime}&lt;/li&gt;)}
            &lt;/ul&gt;
            &lt;input type="text" placeholder='input anime name' id='animeInput' /&gt;
            &lt;button&gt;Add Anime&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;/form&gt;
    )
}

function App() {
  return (
      &lt;AnimeList /&gt;
  );
}

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(&lt;App /&gt;);</code></pre>
<pre class="snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/react/18.3.1/umd/react.production.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/react-dom/18.3.1/umd/react-dom.production.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;div id="root"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>
<p>Moreover, usual way of working with <code>input</code> elements is to make them <a href="https://medium.com/@codeyourthoughts48/what-are-controlled-elements-in-react-beginners-guide-c1c8d4a9582b" rel="nofollow noreferrer">controlled elements</a>, i.e. you control their value via state:</p>
<pre><code>// first define state
const [newAnime, setNewAnime] = useState(&quot;&quot;);

// then in returned JSX
return (
    &lt;&gt;
        ...
        &lt;input
            type=&quot;text&quot;
            placeholder=&quot;input anime name&quot;
            value={newAnime}
            onChange={(e) =&gt; setNewAnime(e.target.value)}
        /&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/&gt;
)
</code></pre>
<p>With controlled component approach you can use state <code>newAnime</code> directly, instead of getting it from DOM element.</p>
